    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-08T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-08T15:00:00-05:00" n="741"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d741">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 341.622a/292a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-08T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 8, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4417. Over five weeks have elapsed since the presentation to the Foreign Office
                    of Department’s 4520, December 1, 1916,<note n="1" xml:id="d741fn1">
                        <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_667">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, Supplement, pp.
                            667</ref>–<ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_678">678</ref>.</note> on the <hi
                        rend="italic">Ausable</hi> and other cases, without any indication as to the
                    attitude of the British Government. Is not the time now opportune to make the
                    proposal of arbitration mentioned in my instruction? I dislike to believe that
                    the British Government would hesitate to adjust cases so similar as these are to
                    the <hi rend="italic">Trent</hi> case.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
